# flaky-test.loop
# TEACHES: making a FLAKY test reliable — one that sometimes passes, sometimes fails.
# A single green run is NOT proof of a fix here: flakiness hides between runs.
# So the finish line runs the test MANY times in a loop and is done only when zero
# of those runs fail. The reflect step focuses on the usual flakiness causes
# (timing, ordering, shared state, randomness) instead of "just rerun and hope".

loop "stabilize the flaky upload test":
  goal: the upload test is reliable — it passes consistently, not just occasionally

  # Run it 20 times in a row; the command exits 0 only if NONE of those runs fail.
  # That turns "passed once" into "passes every time", the real goal for flakiness.
  done when "for i in $(seq 20); do pnpm test upload || exit 1; done" passes

  # Context: the test, the code under test, and anything async/time/IO related.
  look at: upload.spec.ts, src/upload.ts, and the last failure

  each cycle: plan, then act, then observe

  # KEY for flaky tests: don't just retry — reflect on WHY it's flaky.
  # Common culprits: race conditions, fixed sleeps, test ordering / shared state,
  # unmocked clocks, network, or randomness. Name the cause before changing code.
  when it fails: reflect on the source of flakiness such as timing or shared state or randomness, then plan again

  # Have a human eyeball the fix before we call it stable; flakiness is sneaky.
  a human reviews before stopping

  when it passes and the goal is met: stop

  # If it's still intermittently failing after several rounds, escalate to a human.
  after 6 tries: stop and warn "upload test still flaky after 6 rounds — needs a human to dig in"
